## CRITICAL NOTES

Never import better-sqlite3 anywhere after this migration.
Search the entire codebase for 'better-sqlite3' and
'Database from' to catch any missed imports.

Transactions: any operation touching multiple tables must
use db.transaction(). The agent tools (add_layer,
edit_element, etc) touch scenes + layers + snapshots —
always wrap in a transaction so partial failures roll back.

Connection pool in Next.js: Next.js hot-reload creates
new module instances in dev, which would create multiple
pools. Use a global singleton pattern:

```ts
// In /lib/db/index.ts, replace pool creation with:
const globalForDb = global as unknown as { pool: Pool };

const pool = globalForDb.pool ?? new Pool({
  connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL,
  ...
});

if (process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production') {
  globalForDb.pool = pool;
}
```

Null userId: in local mode with no auth, userId is null
on all projects. This is intentional. All queries that
filter by userId must handle null:
  WHERE user_id = $1 OR ($1 IS NULL AND user_id IS NULL)
Or use the isNull() Drizzle helper.

Migrations in production: never use drizzle-kit push in
production (it drops and recreates). Use drizzle-kit generate
to create migration files, commit them, then run migrate()
on startup. The setup.ts script handles this correctly.

Scene HTML files: these live in /public/scenes/ on the
filesystem, not in Postgres. Postgres stores the layer data
(generatedCode, elements, config). The HTML files are
generated FROM the database data by writeSceneHTML().
When migrating from SQLite, regenerate all scene HTML files
by calling writeSceneHTML() for every scene.
```